  "title": "Bullying and Ostracism Screening Scales (BOSS): Development and Applications",
  "abstract": "Abstract The Bullying and Ostracism Screening Scale (BOSS) is a brief self-report measure for detecting bullying and ostracism in pediatric populations. Preliminary psychometric studies with 426 children 10â€“14 years old from pediatric clinics and schools yielded a promising measure with screening sensitivity superior to parent report. Additional analyses with 1076 students support BOSS factor structure and utility. Bullying and ostracism were significantly correlated with self-reported depression and threats to self-esteem, belonging, control, and meaningful existence. The BOSS is a cost-effective instrument for health care professionals wishing to screen for bullying and ostracism in pediatric populations with somatic, academic, emotional, and behavioral issues. ACKNOWLEDGMENTS This research was supported in part by consecutive Citadel Foundation Faculty Research grants awarded to Dr. Saylor, by a Medical University of South Carolina Fellowship Research grant awarded to Dr. Twyman, and by the National Science Foundation Grant No. 0519209 awarded to Dr.Williams. We gratefully acknowledge the contributions of Danielle Saia, Lynn Wogamon, Rachel Santorelli, Sara Knippenberg, Evan Sola, Kimberly Veronee, Melissa-Miles Dunn, Kristina Kenny, James Carpenter, and Tasha Burton at various stages of this research. We also thank participating families, schools, and pediatric clinics. Illustrations in Figure 1 were contributed by Paul Christian Saylor. Notes",
